  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in the real world, especially in places like Naples where the education system can feel disconnected from practical skills. It's when people, particularly those from underrepresented groups, start to worry that their performance might confirm a negative stereotype about their group. For me, growing up in a family where my dad has a bachelor's degree but my mom only went to primary school, I often felt like I had to prove myself in school because I wasn't 'smart enough' compared to others. This anxiety can make someone avoid challenging tasks or give up early, which is exactly what happens in STEM fields. I think we absolutely should address it, but not with top-down solutions that ignore the real-world context of people like me who work full-time jobs, clean offices, or fix things around town. Instead, we need to create spaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes without fear of judgment. In my neighborhood, I've noticed that when people are encouraged to ask questions without shame, they're more likely to engage deeply with learning. So, addressing stereotype threat means listening to those who are already struggling and building systems that work for them, not just for the people who are already doing well. It's about creating a culture where being a 'good student' isn't about fitting into a mold but about finding your own way to learn.",
